ks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"family","header":"First cousin to educator Emma Hart Willard","body":"Philomela Hurlbut was a first cousin to Emma Hart Willard (1787-1870) — the pioneering women's-education advocate who founded the Troy Female Seminary in 1821, one of the first higher-education institutions for women in the United States. Emma later acknowledged the dual Hooker-line connection running through both the Hart and Hurlbut branches of their shared ancestry, the two lines converging through the marriage that united the Hurlbut and Hinsdale families."},{"number":2,"category":"family","header":"Married her father's patient's brother","body":"Philomela married John Hinsdale of Connecticut, brother of Lydia Hinsdale Hart — Lydia having been Philomela's father Dr. James Hurlbut's patient early in life. The doctor-patient connection that brought the Hurlbut and Hinsdale families into orbit produced the next-generation marriage between Philomela and John, with John being Lydia's brother and therefore Philomela's eventual brother-in-law via the Hart-Hinsdale connection."},{"number":3,"category":"family","header":"Born Farmington CT 1754, died New Britain 1790","body":"Philomela Hurlbut was born about 1754 in Farmington Connecticut and died December 22, 1790 in New Britain Connecticut at about age thirty-six. The short life — about thirty-six years — was typical of late-eighteenth-century childbearing-age mortality in colonial-and-Republic Connecticut. She is the documentary link between the Hurlbut and Hinsdale families of the Hooker tree."}],"slug":"philomela-hurlbut-1754"},"X01290":{"id":"X01290","has_descendants_documented":false,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":false,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"tags":[],"sources":[],"gender":"male","number_of_marriages":1,"marriages":[{"